data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `BackgroundProcessor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | App crashes at runtime |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never thrown** | Catch block is dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | App crashes at runtime |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state — it can fire mid-`finally` block, mid-lock, or mid-write, leaving objects half-initialized. .NET 8 enforces cooperative cancellation instead.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _workerTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cooperative shutdown requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit loop cleanly; finally still runs
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel(); // signals all token observers immediately

        // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
        if (_workerTask != null)
        {
            if (!_workerTask.Wait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)))
            {
                // Log warning — the work didn't stop in time.
                // In .NET 8 there is NO safe way to forcibly kill it.
                // Fix the blocking call to respect the token instead.
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

**1. Blocking calls MUST accept `CancellationToken`**
The old code relied on `Abort()` to interrupt a blocked `GetNextItem()`. In .NET 8, if `GetNextItem()` doesn't observe the token, `Stop()` hangs until it returns naturally. Refactor it:

```csharp
// ❌ Old — uninterruptible
var item = queue.Take();

// ✅ New — cancellable
var item = queue.Take(token);       // BlockingCollection<T>
var item = await channel.ReadAsync(token); // System.Threading.Channels
```

**2. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` silently becomes dead code**
The compiler won't warn you. The rollback logic never fires unless you replace it with `OperationCanceledException` as shown above.

**3. `Thread.ResetAbort()` crashes at runtime, not compile time**
It compiles fine (the API exists) but throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. This is a runtime landmine.

**4. `volatile bool` is insufficient for cancellation**
A `volatile bool` can't wake a blocked thread. `CancellationToken` integrates with `WaitHandle`, async APIs, and `BlockingCollection` — it actually interrupts waits.

**5. `Task.Run` vs `Thread` with `IsBackground = true`**
`Task.Run` uses the thread pool (already background threads). Avoid `new Thread()` unless you need a dedicated long-running thread, in which case use:
```csharp
Task.Factory.StartNew(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token),
    _cts.Token, TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning, TaskScheduler.Default);
```

---

### If This Is a Hosted App (ASP.NET Core, Worker Service)

Inherit from `BackgroundService` — it handles the lifecycle for you:

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
        }
    }
}
```

Register with `builder.Services.AddHostedService<BackgroundProcessor>();` and the host manages start/stop/cancellation automatically.
